lumbar.textareatext: Normal lordotic curve, no scoliosis, swelling/edema or scars.

lumbar.label: Lumbar Ranges of Motion Table A-2 page 597: AMA Estimated Normal: Flexion (60D), Extension (25D), Lateral Bend (Right and Left) (25D). Motion is reported right over left side in Degrees (D). Measurements are obtained with an inclinometer (two location method).
lumbar.textareatext: Enter three consecutive true spinal angle measurements (Top spinal segment reading (D lower spinal segment reading (D); Example: T12 flexion 60 DS1 flexion 17D = Flexion true spinal angle measurement 43 D). Lumbar plane measurements are valid if they are measured within 5D if the average is < 50D, or within 10D if the average is > 50D. A maximum of six measurement attempts may be performed.

lumbar.label: Actual inclinometer measurements of the range of motion are only required for PR-4 (Permanent & Stationary) reports. Visual estimates of the range of motion may be adequate for Doctor's First reports and PR-2 reports.
Maximum Flexion Sacrum S1
lumbar.textareatext: This measurement is required for injuries that a) have fractures at more than one level in the same spinal region or b) bilateral or multilevel radiculopathy in the same spinal region or c) multilevel motion segment alteration (includes multilevel fusion) in the same spinal region or d) recurrent disk herniation or stenosis with radiculopathy at the same or a different level in the same spinal region.

lumbar.label: Maximum Extension Sacrum S1
lumbar.textareatext: This measurement is required for injuries that a) have fractures at more than one level in the same spinal region or b) bilateral or multilevel radiculopathy in the same spinal region or c) multilevel motion segment alteration (includes multilevel fusion) in the same spinal region or d) recurrent disk herniation or stenosis with radiculopathy at the same or a different level in the same spinal region.

lumbar.label: Straight-Leg Raised Angle
lumbar.textareatext: Record the straight leg-raised angle by placing an inclinometer on each tibial crest (shin) with the knee extended and the hip flexed.
